<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="chi-square-test-summary-5-1">
  <title>Summary of Chi-squared Tests</title>

  <assemblage xml:id="chi-square-test-summary-box">
    <title>Summary of Chi-squared Tests</title>
    <p><em>Test of homogeneity:</em> Data are independent random samples from <m>I</m> different populations/processes or from a randomized experiment with <m>I</m> treatments.</p>
    <p><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>H_0\!: \pi_1 = \cdots = \pi_I</m> where <m>\pi_i</m> is the probability of success for population (treatment) <m>i</m>.</p>
    <p><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>H_a\!:</m> at least one <m>\pi_i</m> differs from the rest.</p>
    <p>OR</p>
    <p><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>H_0</m>: the response variable distributions are the same in each population (treatment).</p>
    <p><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>H_a</m>: at least one population (treatment) distribution differs from the others.</p>

    <p><em>Test of association:</em> Data are one random sample from a large population, cross-classified by two categorical variables.</p>
    <p><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>H_0\!:</m> no association between <em>variable 1</em> and <em>variable 2</em> in the population.</p>
    <p><nbsp/><nbsp/><m>H_a\!:</m> there is an association between <em>variable 1</em> and <em>variable 2</em>.</p>

    <sidebyside widths="62% 33%" margins="0% 0%" valign="top">
      <stack>
        <p><alert>Chi-square Statistic:</alert> <m>\chi^2 = \sum_{i=1}^{r} \sum_{j=1}^{c} \frac{(Observed_{ij}-Expected_{ij})^2}{Expected_{ij}}</m></p>
      </stack>
      <image source="images/chisqDist.jpeg" width="100%">
        <description>Chi-square distribution used for upper-tail p-values</description>
      </image>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>The (upper tail) p-value is calculated from the chi-square distribution with <m>(r - 1)(c - 1)</m> degrees of freedom.</p>

    <p><alert>Technical conditions:</alert> at least 80% of expected counts are at least 5, and all expected counts are at least 1.</p>

      <p><alert>Follow-up analysis</alert>: After computing the p-value, examine the largest cell contributions or residuals to describe where observed counts differ most from expected counts.</p>

  </assemblage>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Technology Instructions</title>
    <p>Use the hint links below to reveal software-specific instructions.</p>
    <hint>
      <title>Applet Instructions</title>
      <p>Use the <url href="http://www.rossmanchance.com/applets/ChisqShuffle.htm">Analyzing Two-way Tables applet</url>.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>You can paste in raw data or the two way table. Remember to use one-word variable names and categories.</li>
        <li>Check the Show Table and Show <m>X^2</m> output boxes.</li>
      </ul>
    </hint>
    <hint>
      <title>R Instructions</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Create a matrix of the observed counts and use <c>chisq.test(matrix)</c>.</li>
        <li>To access the expected counts and (unsquared) chi-squared contributions use <c>chisq.test(matrix)$expected</c> and <c>chisq.test(matrix)$residuals</c>.</li>
      </ul>
    </hint>
    <hint>
      <title>JMP Instructions</title>
      <sidebyside widths="62% 33%" margins="0% 0%" valign="top">
        <stack>
          <ul>
            <li>With two nominal columns (and perhaps a column of counts), choose Analyze &gt; Fit Y by X. Report the Pearson chi-square and p-value.</li>
            <li>Use the Contingency Table hot spot to turn on the Cell Chi Square values.</li>
          </ul>
        </stack>
        <image source="images/5-1-sumJMP.jpeg" width="100%">
          <description>JMP data page layout for chi-square test setup</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </hint>
  </paragraphs>


</section>
